Lab One: Exploring Table Data¶

*Ayan Khan, Anika Saiprabhu, Victoria Valdez*

1. Business Understanding¶

Educational policy aims to ensure that all students are able to succeed in their respective academic environments. In order to help their rankings, universities attempt to maximize graduation rates and retention rates while minimizing dropouts.

Towards this end, it becomes important for universities to understand the factors at play that may affect student success and retention in order to best address the needs of students most at risk of dropping out.

We chose a dataset from the UCI ML repository regarding student success rates. This dataset has 4424 instances and 36 features, including numerical and categorical data.

  • Dataset: UCI Machine Learning Repository - Student Dropout and Academic Success

  • URL: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/697/predict+students+dropout+and+academic+success

By understanding the different factors that affect a student's success, schools can pass policy that will best support students most at risk for failing or dropping out. By understanding the factors at play, universities can proactively pass policies aimed at recruitment, retention, and support both before and after admittance.

This would help both students in their academic journey and universities attempting to raise their rankings.

2.2 Data Information and Data Types:¶

The data information and data types from the original dataset are as listed above.

For the most part, it would be best to represent each data attribute the way it's listed, but the following attributes would benefit from using a different data type:

  • Course: string instead of int
  • Nationality: string instead of int

For these variables, it would be best to work with them as integers, but they are thought of as booleans:

  • Displaced, Educational special needs, Debtor, Tuition fees up to date, Scholarship holder, International

The following data attributes will not contribute meaningfully to our analysis:

  • Application mode, Application order, Admission grade, Previous qualification (grade)

2.4.2 Cleaning the data¶

  1. Courses

    The first thing we did to lean the data is to replace all course numbers in the data with the corresponding course names. Since the numbers aren't hierarchical, there's little use in keeping the numbers in the dataset when processing. Names make this data more easy to understand, especially when analyzing the data categorically.

In [ ]:
# Replaces course numbers with corresponding names

df["Course"].replace(to_replace = [33, 171, 8014, 9003, 9070, 9085, 9119, 9130, 9147, 9238, 9254, 9500, 9556, 9670, 9773, 9853, 9991],
                    value = ["Biofuel production", "Animation and multimedia", "Social service (evening)", "Agronomy", "Communication design", "Veterinary nursing", 
                            "Informatics engineering", "Equinculture", "Management", "Social service", "Tourism", "Nursing", "Oral hygiene", "Advertising and marketing management",
                            "Journalism and communication", "Basic Education", "Management (evening)"], inplace = True)

  1. Mother/Father Qualification

    The mother/father qualification data isn't hierarchically numbered. Additionally, many of the categories are redundant. I grouped several similar education levels to make the data easier to understand. I've cleaned the data by reclassifying the categories from least education, 1, to most education, 14. The original number is indicated by parentheses in the following ranking:

    1. Can't read or write - (35, 34)
    2. Can read without 4th year of schooling - (36)
    3. Elementary Education (4th/5th year) - (37)
    4. Middle Education (6th-8th year) - (38, 29, 30, 26, 11)
    5. High School Education (9th-11th year) - (12, 14, 27, 19)
    6. Completed Secondary Education (12th year) - (1)
    7. General commerce course - (18)
    8. Technical-professional course - (22)
    9. Technological specialization course - (39)
    10. Specialized higher studies course - (41)
    11. Professional higher technical course - (42)
    12. Bachelor's Degree - (3, 40, 2)
    13. Master's Degree - (4, 43)
    14. Doctoral Degree - (5, 44)

    The following categories were discarded because they did not provide information.

    • Frequency of Higher Education (6) - this appears to be a frequency rather than a qualification leevel

    • Unkown (34) - this does not provide any information

In [ ]:
#calculate the percentage of students in each category for each nationality
nationality_counts = df['Nationality'].value_counts()
nationality_percentages = {}

#normalize data by count of students in each category for each nationality
for nationality in nationality_counts.index:
    nationality_df = df[df['Nationality'] == nationality]
    total_students = len(nationality_df)
    graduate_count = len(nationality_df[nationality_df['Target'] == 'Graduate'])
    dropout_count = len(nationality_df[nationality_df['Target'] == 'Dropout'])
    
    graduate_percentage = (graduate_count / total_students) * 100
    dropout_percentage = (dropout_count / total_students) * 100
    
    nationality_percentages[nationality] = {'Graduate': graduate_percentage, 'Dropout': dropout_percentage}

#create a dataframe for plotting
plot_df = pd.DataFrame(nationality_percentages).transpose()

#create the bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plot_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=['lightgreen', 'lightcoral'], edgecolor='gray')
plt.title('Graduate vs Dropout Rate by Nationality (Normalized)')
plt.xlabel('Nationality')
plt.ylabel('Percentage')
plt.ylim(0, 100)  # Set y-axis limit to ensure correct scaling
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.legend(title='Target', loc='upper right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

<Figure size 1200x600 with 0 Axes>

This graph shows that certain countries such as Germany and Romania are more likely to graduate while other countries such as Colombia and Russia are more likely to drop out. The information in this graph, while normalized, is still not the most reliable since it does feature a small sample size, with the exception of Portugal.

3.3 Conclusion¶

The study reveals significant insights into the factors influencing educational outcomes among students of various nationalities, marital statuses, genders, financial conditions, and parental educational backgrounds. Predominantly focusing on Portuguese students, the analysis identified that nationality plays a crucial role in determining the likelihood of a student dropping out or graduating. Russian, Lithuanian, Angolan, Colombian, and Moldovan students showing a higher propensity for dropping out. Conversely, Mozambican, Romanian, Dutch, English, and Colombian students demonstrated lower dropout rates. Notably, Portuguese students had a 60% likelihood of graduation.

Marital status emerged as a significant factor, with married students exhibiting higher dropout rates compared to their single counterparts. Furthermore, gender differences were apparent, especially when intersected with marital status; married women were more likely to drop out than married men, highlighting a gender disparity in educational outcomes.

Financial indicators also strongly correlated with students' educational trajectories. Debtors and those with outstanding tuition fees were more likely to drop out, whereas scholarship recipients, who generally had their tuition fees up to date, were more likely to graduate. This suggests that financial stability and support mechanisms, such as scholarships, are critical in promoting educational success.

Parental qualifications indicated a correlation between higher parental education levels and increased graduation rates among students. Although this correlation was not as pronounced as anticipated, it underscores the potential influence of parental education on student outcomes. The absence of data on some students' parental education levels suggests a need for caution in interpreting these findings, as unreported backgrounds could skew the results.

Overall, the study highlights the multifaceted nature of student educational success. It underscores the importance of addressing these factors holistically to support student success and reduce dropout rates. Moving forward, university administrators must implement strategies that cater to these diverse needs, ensuring that all students have the chance to succeed.
